or": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "1ef7c2d4fb589e15195096f1f9f7458d0d7342e9addc650f8db3fb55b46d7fb1"}}, "hash": "b4bfc1e780fcaa177fcf3e7b9b1f6cf9a6151fde642d81e38762708906fe7e9f", "text": "When flood water started entering her home in July 2021, Shubhangi Kamble fled leaving her belongings behind. On her way out, though, she quickly grabbed two notebooks. Over the weeks and months ahead, these two books, 172 pages each, would help her save many lives. For that was the time when her village, Arjunwad, in Maharashtra\u2019s Kolhapur district, was already dealing with another calamity \u2013 a rapid rise in Covid-19 cases. And neatly written on the pages of Shubhangi\u2019s notebooks was all the information related to the coronavirus cases in the village, including contact numbers, address, details of other members in the family, their medical history, health records, and so on. \u201cCovid reports [of RT-PCR tests conducted in the village] would first come to me,\u201d says the 33-year-old Accredited Social Health Activist (ASHA), one of a million women community health care workers appointed under India\u2019s National Rural Health Mission of 2005. Her notes helped her track down a Covid-positive villager who had been moved to a flood relief camp in Shirol taluka , exposing at least 5,000 other people to the virus. \u201cBecause of the floods, many people\u2019s phones were switched off or out of network coverage,\u201d she says. Shubhangi, who had moved to her mother\u2019s house in Terwad, 15 kilometres away, immediately searched her handwritten records and found phone numbers of some others at the camp. \u201cI somehow managed to contact the patient.\u201d <img alt=\"A house in Arjunwad village that was destroyed by the floods in 2019\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/02a-IMG_0237-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/02a-IMG_0237-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-.height-1120.jpg\" style=\" height:770px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain A house in Arjunwad village that was destroyed by the floods in 2019 var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); <img alt=\"An ASHA worker examining the damage in the public health sub-centre in Kolhapur's Bhendavade village, which was ravaged by the floods in 2021\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/02b-IMG_7005-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/02b-IMG_7005-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"Medical supplies destroyed in the deluge\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/02c-IMG_6999-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/02c-IMG_6999-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: An ASHA worker examining the damage in the public health sub-centre in Kolhapur's Bhendavade village, which was ravaged by the floods in 2021. Right: Medical supplies destroyed in the deluge var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); She also arranged a bed at a Covid centre set up in the nearby Agar village and the patient was swiftly moved there. \u201cHad I not taken the notebook, thousands of people would have been infected,\u201d she says. That was not the first time Shubhangi had averted a major crisis for her village or put her duty above herself. After the 2019 floods (in August), she reported at work even before she could tend to her own damaged mud house.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b73ceb7e-48a6-4d43-ba1e-042be32277eb": {"__data__": {"id_": "b73ceb7e-48a6-4d43-ba1e-042be32277eb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "723f6b73ad3bf39a567c2a7d2d7078c3aeebd4a12775ff488a051af398b3c809"}, "2": {"node_id": "bcd57096-3484-4f98-a7c8-fde3af8248d6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "b4bfc1e780fcaa177fcf3e7b9b1f6cf9a6151fde642d81e38762708906fe7e9f"}}, "hash": "1ef7c2d4fb589e15195096f1f9f7458d0d7342e9addc650f8db3fb55b46d7fb1", "text": "\u201cI was busy surveying the damage of the entire village as per the village panchayat\u2019 s orders,\u201d she says. For over three months after that, she went around the village talking to flood survivors and seeing devastation everywhere. What she saw and heard disturbed her immensely; she started experiencing anxiety and stress while noting down the losses incurred by the over 1,100 households she surveyed. \u201cI was neglecting my mental health,\u201d she says. \u201cBut what option did I have?\u201d Even before she had recovered from the trauma caused by the floods that year, she was at the forefront of Covid relief in 2020. And even as the pandemic raged, she was back to helping those affected by floods in July 2021. \u201cFloods and Covid together meant a disaster much larger than we could ever imagine,\u201d says Shubhangi. The continued neglect of her own mental health eventually began to manifest in various ways. In April 2022, she was diagnosed with pneumonia and moderate anaemia. \u201cI was feverish for eight days but, because of work, I kept ignoring the symptoms,\u201d she says. Her haemoglobin fell to 7.9, well below the ideal level for women (12-16 grams per deciliter of blood), and she had to be hospitalised. <img alt=\"ASHA worker Shubhangi Kamble\u2019s X-ray report. In April 2022, she was diagnosed with pneumonia and also moderate anaemia\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/03a-IMG_6186-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/03a-IMG_6186-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"Shubhangi walking to a remote part of Arjunwad village to conduct health care surveys. ASHAs like her deal with rains, heat waves and floods without any aids\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/03b-IMG_6261-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/03b-IMG_6261-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: ASHA worker Shubhangi Kamble\u2019s X-ray report. In April 2022, she was diagnosed with pneumonia and also moderate anaemia. Right: Shubhangi walking to a remote part of Arjunwad village to conduct health care surveys . ASHAs like her deal with rains, heat waves and floods without any aids var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); Two months on, just as she", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4c254bb7-9ba1-4ab7-a399-446d3951814a": {"__data__": {"id_": "4c254bb7-9ba1-4ab7-a399-446d3951814a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "7a36315aa7f046ac109a25414e7633f6e68b46fab506c06003cae6e868bfa29f"}, "3": {"node_id": "8625fe36-76b5-4c4a-9351-8aa1b53028d2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "e94dda850e37cf1d71274b2e9cc36866cc0ebc38a2948ccbd2d6f3639ec13740"}}, "hash": "18a4d9fbb6baca504fc6bae94fdd3a7c45680d61e8a6871399db3c5dae6f1c32", "text": "was recovering, her village witnessed heavy rains \u2013 and Shubhangi once again started experiencing stress seeing the rapid rise in water levels. \u201cOnce, we would eagerly await the rains, but now with every rainfall we fear another flood,\u201d she says. \u201cThis year in August, the water was rising so quickly that I couldn\u2019t sleep for several days.\u201d [Also read: In Kolhapur, athletes get that sinking feeling ] Despite continued treatment, Shubhangi\u2019s haemoglobin level remains low; she also complains of dizziness and fatigue. But there is no rest or healing in sight. \u201cAs ASHAs, we are supposed to become a support system when we ourselves are completely devastated,\u201d she says. ***** ASHA worker Chhaya Kamble, 38, from Shirol\u2019s Ganeshwadi village, remembers the 2021 floods in great detail. \u201cThe rescue boat was sailing above our house,\u201d she says. Like Shubhangi, Chhaya too was back at work as soon as the water started receding; her home would have to wait. \u201cAll of us [the six ASHA workers of Ganweshwadi] first went to the sub-centre,\u201d she says. Since the floods had damaged the building, they created a makeshift sub-centre at a resident\u2019s house. \u201cEvery day, several people affected by pneumonia, cholera, typhoid, skin diseases, fever, and more would come [to the sub-centre].\u201d This duty lasted a whole month, without even a day off. <img alt=\"Chhaya Kamble (right) conducting a health survey in Ganeshwadi village\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/04a-IMG_6815-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/04a-IMG_6815-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD.height-1120.jpg\" style=\" height:770px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Chhaya Kamble (right) conducting a health survey in Ganeshwadi village var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); <img alt=\"Chhaya says the changes in climate and the recurring floods have affected her mental health\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/04b-IMG_6823-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/04b-IMG_6823-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/04c-IMG_6797-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/04c-IMG_6797-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: Chhaya says the changes in climate and the recurring floods have affected her mental health. Right: Here she is compiling the survey records var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); \u201cSeeing everyone in tears does affect you,\u201d says Chhaya. \u201cUnfortunately, there is no mental health care facility for us. So, how do we heal?\u201d As it turns out, she did not. Her stress levels continued to rise and she soon began experiencing shortness of breath. \u201cI kept ignoring it thinking it must be because of the workload.\u201d Within a few months Chhaya was diagnosed with asthma. \u201cThe doctor said it was because of the tremendous stress,\u201d she says; there are enough studies that establish the link between stress and asthma.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8625fe36-76b5-4c4a-9351-8aa1b53028d2": {"__data__": {"id_": "8625fe36-76b5-4c4a-9351-8aa1b53028d2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "7a36315aa7f046ac109a25414e7633f6e68b46fab506c06003cae6e868bfa29f"}, "2": {"node_id": "4c254bb7-9ba1-4ab7-a399-446d3951814a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "18a4d9fbb6baca504fc6bae94fdd3a7c45680d61e8a6871399db3c5dae6f1c32"}}, "hash": "e94dda850e37cf1d71274b2e9cc36866cc0ebc38a2948ccbd2d6f3639ec13740", "text": "While medicines are helping Chhaya, she cannot stop worrying about the rapid changes in the climate. During the heatwave of March-April this year, for instance, she started experiencing spells of dizziness and breathlessness. \"It was the toughest time to be on duty. I felt like my skin was burning,\u201d she recalls. Research has found that high temperatures can affect cognitive functioning , even leading to a rise in suicide rate , violence and aggression . Many other ASHA workers report similar symptoms as Chhaya. \u201cThis is not odd. These are symptoms of seasonal affective disorder [SAD],\u201d says Kolhapur-based clinical psychologist Shalmali Ranmale-Kakade. SAD is a form of depression triggered by a change in season. While symptoms are more commonly associated with winters in higher latitude countries, there is increased awareness about the disorder affecting people in tropical countries like India too. <img alt=\"Shubhangi Kamble weighing a 22-day-old newborn in Kolhapur\u2019s Arjunwad village\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/05a-IMG_6211-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/05a-IMG_6211-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD.height-1120.jpg\" style=\" height:770px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Shubhangi Kamble weighing a 22-day-old newborn in Kolhapur\u2019s Arjunwad village var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); <img alt=\"Stranded villagers being taken to safety after the floods\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/05b-IMG_6281-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/05b-IMG_6281-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"Floodwater in Shirol taluka in July 2021\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/05c-IMG_5954-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/05c-IMG_5954-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: Stranded villagers being taken to safety after the floods. Right: Floodwater in Shirol taluka in July 2021 var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); \u201cAs the climate changes, I start feeling anxious; I feel dizzy. Aata mala aajibat sahan hoina jhalay [I can\u2019t take this anymore],\u201d says Shubhangi. \u201cAlmost every flood-affected ASHA is experiencing some form of stress, which is now leading to chronic illnesses. Yet, the government does not help us despite saving so many people.\u201d Not that health authorities don\u2019t acknowledge the problem. The question is whether their response is adequate, or even correct. Dr. Prasad Datar, Taluka Health Officer of the nearby flood-affected Hatkanangle taluka , says health care workers in the region are \u201coverworked and stressed\u201d since the floods and Covid. \u201cTo help address these concerns, we organise cultural programmes for ASHA workers annually,\u201d he adds. However, ASHA union leader Netradipa Patil, based in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2f9e7b33-8fbb-49ef-8261-3730c083b313": {"__data__": {"id_": "2f9e7b33-8fbb-49ef-8261-3730c083b313", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "f4dfbdbf70a01996ab04d0e59e9d16d909bf39c685c9061c5411138a90a57ea9"}, "3": {"node_id": "694666e4-b43a-4fb4-a2c7-0b325adedbb7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "65fb3b4b43b9a4d573c7597884225e4f3739203ae1b25e3dc9575ff8fa731d3c"}}, "hash": "9ffe34d9f82f267af271c354b482435286dd7ad4361de124d15860e9f0aef0b6", "text": "Kolhapur\u2019s Shirol taluka, believes these programmes are not helping. \u201cWhen I voiced the mental health concerns to the authorities, they dismissed it saying we need to learn to deal with such situations,\u201d she adds. Ranmale-Kakade says ASHA workers need therapy and counselling so they are able to cope with the persistent stress. \u201cThe helping hand, too, needs help,\u201d she says. \u201cUnfortunately, this doesn\u2019t happen in our society.\u201d Moreover, she adds, many frontline health care workers are so much in \u2018helping mode\u2019 that they often don\u2019t identify their own burnout, frustration and emotional burden. Dealing with recurring stressors, such as the rapidly changing local climatic patterns, requires increased intensity and frequency of interventions, she adds. ***** The changing climate patterns have more than one role to play in the declining mental health of ASHA workers in Kolhapur. <img alt=\"ASHA worker Netradipa Patil administering oral vaccine to a child at the Rural Hospital, Shirol\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/06a-IMG_1814-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/06a-IMG_1814-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:410px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"Netradipa hugs a woman battling suicidal thoughts\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/06b-IMG_20210605_131331-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASH.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/06b-IMG_20210605_131331-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:410px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: ASHA worker Netradipa Patil administering oral vaccine to a child at the Rural Hospital, Shirol. Right: Netradipa hugs a woman battling suicidal thoughts var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); <img alt=\"Rani Kohli (left) was out to work in Bhendavade even after floods destroyed her house in 2021\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/06c-IMG_6951-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/06c-IMG_6951-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"An ASHA checking temperature at the height of Covid-19\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/06d-IMG_4229-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/06d-IMG_4229-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: Rani Kohli (left) was out to work in Bhendavade even after floods destroyed her house in 2021 . Right: An ASHA checking temperature at the height of Covid-19 var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); Despite the immense load on them \u2013 each ASHA handles over 70 health care tasks for 1,000 people in a village, including ensuring safer pregnancies and universal immunisation \u2013 these health workers remain poorly paid and exploited. Netradipa points out that ASHAs in Maharashtra are paid a meagre Rs. 3,500-5,000 per month, that too with a delay of at least three months.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "694666e4-b43a-4fb4-a2c7-0b325adedbb7": {"__data__": {"id_": "694666e4-b43a-4fb4-a2c7-0b325adedbb7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "f4dfbdbf70a01996ab04d0e59e9d16d909bf39c685c9061c5411138a90a57ea9"}, "2": {"node_id": "2f9e7b33-8fbb-49ef-8261-3730c083b313", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "9ffe34d9f82f267af271c354b482435286dd7ad4361de124d15860e9f0aef0b6"}}, "hash": "65fb3b4b43b9a4d573c7597884225e4f3739203ae1b25e3dc9575ff8fa731d3c", "text": "\u201cEven today, we are considered volunteers, which denies us minimum wages and other benefits,\u201d she elaborates. ASHA workers receive what the government calls a \u2018performance-based incentive,\u2019 which means that they are paid upon the completion of certain tasks in their community. There is no fixed honorarium and the pay varies from one state to another. Many ASHA workers, therefore, cannot survive solely on their income from taking care of the community\u2019s health care needs. Shubhangi, for instance, would double up as an agricultural labourer to make ends meet. \u201cAfter the 2019 and 2021 floods, I could not find work for three months as the fields were destroyed,\u201d she says. \u201cWith the changing climate, the rains have become unpredictable. Even if it rains for some time, it destroys everything, including our hopes of getting farm work.\u201d In July 2021, heavy rain and floods affected 4.43 lakh hectares of crop area across 24 districts of Maharashtra, including Kolhapur. Since 2019, recurring floods and destruction to property as well as loss of agricultural work have forced Shubhangi to seek small, high-interest loans totalling Rs. 100,000 from different moneylenders. She even had to pawn her gold, and shift to a 10x15 feet tin shanty as she could not afford to rebuild the old house. \u201cBoth in 2019 and 2021, floodwater entered the house in less than 30 hours. We could save nothing,\u201d says her husband, Sanjay, 37, who has now started working as a mason because there is not enough work to be found as an agricultural labourer. <img alt=\"After the floodwater had receded, Shubhangi Kamble was tasked with disinfecting water (left) and making a list (right) of the losses incurred by villagers\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/07a-IMG_7545-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/07a-IMG_7545-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"After the floodwater had receded, Shubhangi Kamble was tasked with disinfecting water (left) and making a list (right) of the losses incurred by villagers\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/07b-IMG_7553-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/07b-IMG_7553-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain After the floodwater had receded, Shubhangi Kamble was tasked with disinfecting water (left) and making a list (right) of the losses incurred by villagers var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); Despite her own losses and suffering, Shubhangi found herself spending more time attending to the relentless demands of her work as an ASHA. Along with surveying the losses caused by the floods, ASHAs were tasked with disinfecting drinking water sources to prevent the spread of water-borne diseases. Many of their tasks are not even paid for, says Netradipa. \u201cFor doing all this post-flood relief work, which caused us", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "78c95844-e25c-4fdf-93e2-fcda0d5651ff": {"__data__": {"id_": "78c95844-e25c-4fdf-93e2-fcda0d5651ff", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "a34c6c99fb7ddebcc50d63c3cc97a1b2906c274c258d8c1a6d7b33cae65792b8"}, "3": {"node_id": "ba59b460-83eb-4b00-91e8-2b7fb5d3bd93", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "318beb604e077ee740a170e0d5348a7c49f0f3f404b2ef47dc49c0c8844300e3"}}, "hash": "f7ec05e4b7ab1c4879e38735fb8b48017631beb8b392663d6b8ff0e51b18d223", "text": "so many mental issues, we were paid nothing. It\u2019s all free labour.\u201d \u201cWe had to visit every house and note down if anyone had any symptoms of water-borne or vector-borne diseases,\u201d says Shubhangi. \u201cASHAs saved several lives by ensuring timely treatment.\u201d Yet, when she herself fell ill in April this year, she received little support from the system. \u201cDespite being a public health care worker, I had to seek treatment in a private hospital and spend Rs. 22,000 because the public hospital was only prescribing medicines whereas I needed to be hospitalised immediately,\u201d she says. Although she receives free folic acid and iron supplements from the public sub-centre, she continues to spend Rs. 500 on additional medicines every month. Chhaya, who earns around Rs. 4,000 a month as an ASHA worker, spends around Rs. 800 on medicines, which she can ill afford. \u201cIn the end, we have accepted the fact that we are social workers. That\u2019s probably why we have to suffer so much,\u201d she says. In 2022, the World Health Organisation (WHO) honoured ASHA workers with the Global Health Leaders Award for making health care accessible by connecting remote communities to the public health system. \u201cWe are all proud of this,\u201d says Chhaya, \u201cbut whenever we ask our seniors about the delayed and meagre payment, they reply that we are doing incredible service for humanity \u2013 \u2018 Payment changla nahi milat, pan tumhala punya milte [You may not be paid well, but earn people's blessings),\u2019 they tell us.\u201d <img alt=\"\u2018For recording 70 health parameters of everyone in the village, we are paid merely 1,500 rupees,\u2019 says Shubhangi\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/08aIMG_7537-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SA.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/08aIMG_7537-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-1120.jpg\" style=\" height:770px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain \u2018For recording 70 health parameters of everyone in the village, we are paid merely 1,500 rupees, \u2019 says Shubhangi var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); <img alt=\"An ASHA dressed as Durga (left) during a protest outside the Collector\u2019s office (right) in Kolhapur. Across India, ASHA workers have been demanding better working conditions, employee status, monthly salary and timely pay among other things\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/08bIMG_5275-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SA.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/08bIMG_5275-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-s.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"An ASHA dressed as Durga (left) during a protest outside the Collector\u2019s office (right) in Kolhapur. Across India, ASHA workers have been demanding better working conditions, employee status, monthly salary and timely pay among other things\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/08c-IMG_5407-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-S.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/08c-IMG_5407-SJ-In-Kolhapur-ASHAs-tell-a-SAD-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:380px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain An ASHA dressed as Durga (left) during a protest outside the Collector\u2019s office (right) in Kolhapur.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ba59b460-83eb-4b00-91e8-2b7fb5d3bd93": {"__data__": {"id_": "ba59b460-83eb-4b00-91e8-2b7fb5d3bd93", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, ASHAs tell a SAD story", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "a34c6c99fb7ddebcc50d63c3cc97a1b2906c274c258d8c1a6d7b33cae65792b8"}, "2": {"node_id": "78c95844-e25c-4fdf-93e2-fcda0d5651ff", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ashas-tell-a-sad-story/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "f7ec05e4b7ab1c4879e38735fb8b48017631beb8b392663d6b8ff0e51b18d223"}}, "hash": "318beb604e077ee740a170e0d5348a7c49f0f3f404b2ef47dc49c0c8844300e3", "text": "Across India, ASHA workers have been demanding better working conditions, employee status, monthly salary and timely pay among other things var container = document.currentScript.parentNode; setImageCaptionWidth(container); A WHO policy brief , however, draws attention to the important issue of the impact of climate change on the mental health of these frontline workers: \u201cThe development of mental health conditions, including depressive, anxiety and stress-related conditions, has been reported following extreme weather events.\u201d Climate events, combined with deteriorating working conditions and apathy towards their situation, are taking a toll on the physical and mental health of ASHAs, says Netradipa. \u201cWhile surveying in the heatwaves this year, many of us reported skin irritation, burning sensation and fatigue,\u201d she says. \u201cWe were not given any protective gear.\u201d Roxy Koll, a climate scientist at Pune\u2019s Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology (IITM) and a contributor to the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change report, emphasises the need for a \u2018climate action plan\u2019 that clearly mentions the periods of the day when heatwaves and extreme events are much stronger. \u201cWe have climate projections for the next several years to decades. So, it is possible to identify those regions and the timings of the day when workers should not be out in the sun,\u201d he says. \u201cThis is not a big task. The data is already there.\u201d In the absence of any official policy or effort in this direction, ASHA workers are left to devise their own ways to deal with the situation. Shubhangi thus starts her day by checking the weather forecast. \u201cI can\u2019t abandon my duty; I can at least try preparing myself to face the day\u2019s weather,\u201d she says. This story is part of a series supported by Internews\u2019 Earth Journalism Network through an independent journalism grant to the reporter. #extreme-climate #excess-rainfall #Covid-19 #climate-change #floods #mental-health #climate-crisis #asha-workers Sanket Jain Share Sanket Jain is a journalist based in Kolhapur, Maharashtra. He is a 2022 PARI Senior Fellow and a 2019 PARI Fellow. Other stories by Sanket Jain Editor : Sangeeta Menon Share Sangeeta Menon is a Mumbai-based writer, editor and communications consultant. Other stories by Sangeeta Menon RELATED STORIES", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "56339859-88c2-4a90-9289-50a2c339a56b": {"__data__": {"id_": "56339859-88c2-4a90-9289-50a2c339a56b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, athletes get that sinking feeling", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "0c3d76896c57e30653890f86c07ebc0be09c67c8c625ae0f307800a7f6273f23"}, "3": {"node_id": "6d692a17-b43a-4ed1-9be1-05a316110b32", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "7710a2600d28180f91507ec8e67616c58f379a5692b86cfddb98eb07c1d31aa6"}}, "hash": "7802dbf92015b9a71ed8d13fbca3e11d476403f6a7ab626a506b4d1309b28ae1", "text": "For Saniya Mullani the first monsoon shower is always a reminder of a prophecy associated with the day of her birth. She was born in July 2005, a week after the deadly floods that claimed over 1,000 lives and affected 20 million people in Maharashtra. \u201cShe is born during the floods; she will spend most of her time in floods,\u201d people are said to have told her parents. Seventeen-year-old Saniya recalled this again when it started raining heavily in the first week of July 2022. \u201cWhenever I hear paani vaadhat challay [The water level is rising], I fear there might be another flood,\u201d says the resident of Bhendavade village in Hatkanangle taluka of Maharashtra's Kolhapur district. The village and its 4,686 residents have witnessed two devastating floods since 2019. \u201cDuring the floods of August 2019, the water rose to seven feet in our house within just 24 hours,\u201d Saniya remembers. The Mullani family managed to escape just as water started entering their home, but the incident left Saniya with deep trauma. Floods struck their village again in July 2021. This time, the family moved to a flood relief camp outside the village for three weeks, returning home only after it was deemed safe by village authorities. A Taekwondo champion, Saniya\u2019s training to become a black belt has suffered a setback ever since the 2019 floods. She has been experiencing fatigue, restlessness, irritability and increased anxiety for the past three years. \u201cI cannot focus on my training,\u201d she says. \u201cMy training is now dependent on the rain.\u201d <img alt=\"Saniya Mullani (centre), 17, prepares for a Taekwondo training session in Kolhapur\u2019s Bhendavade village\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/02a-IMG_4839-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/02a-IMG_4839-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"The floods of 2019 and 2021, which devastated her village and her home, have left her deeply traumatised and unable to focus on her training\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/02b-IMG_4753-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/02b-IMG_4753-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Left: Saniya Mullani (centre), 17, prepares for a Taekwondo training session in Kolhapur\u2019s Bhendavade village. Right: The floods of 2019 and 2021, which devastated her village and her home, have left her deeply traumatised and unable to focus on her training <img alt=\"Young sportswomen from agrarian families are grappling with mental health issues linked to the various impacts of the climate crisis on their lives, including increased financial distress caused by crop loss, mounting debts, and lack of nutrition, among others\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/03-IMG_4793-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/03-IMG_4793-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-1120.jpg\" style=\" height:670px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Young sportswomen from agrarian families are grappling with mental health issues linked to the various impacts of the climate crisis on their lives, including increased financial distress caused by crop loss, mounting debts, and lack of nutrition, among others When the symptoms began, she thought she would get better with time. When that didn't happen, she consulted a private doctor.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6d692a17-b43a-4ed1-9be1-05a316110b32": {"__data__": {"id_": "6d692a17-b43a-4ed1-9be1-05a316110b32", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, athletes get that sinking feeling", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "0c3d76896c57e30653890f86c07ebc0be09c67c8c625ae0f307800a7f6273f23"}, "2": {"node_id": "56339859-88c2-4a90-9289-50a2c339a56b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "7802dbf92015b9a71ed8d13fbca3e11d476403f6a7ab626a506b4d1309b28ae1"}}, "hash": "7710a2600d28180f91507ec8e67616c58f379a5692b86cfddb98eb07c1d31aa6", "text": "When that didn't happen, she consulted a private doctor. Since August 2019, she has visited the doctor at least 20 times, but dizziness, fatigue, body ache, recurring fever, inability to focus, and a constant feeling of \u201ctension and stress,\u201d refuse to go away. \u201cNow, even the thought of going to the doctor causes nightmares,\u201d she says. \u201cA private doctor charges at least 100 rupees for one visit; then there are costs for medicines, multiple tests and follow-ups,\u201d she says. \u201cIn case there's a need for an intravenous drip, we have to shell out 500 rupees for every bottle.\u201d When the consultations failed to help, one of her friends gave her a solution: \u201c Gapp training karaycha [Just go about your training, quietly].\u201d That didn\u2019t help either. To her frustration, when she spoke to her doctor about her deteriorating health, he simply told her, \u201cDon't stress.\u201d Perhaps the most difficult piece of advice for Saniya to follow, given the uncertainty around how the next spell of rain will behave and how her family will be impacted. Saniya's father, Javed, who owns an acre of land, lost over 100,000 kilos of sugarcane during the 2019 and 2021 floods. Heavy rains and the Warna river in spate claimed most of his produce in 2022 too. \u201cSince the 2019 floods, there is no guarantee that you will reap the fruits of what you sow. Every farmer here has to sow at least twice,\u201d says Javed. This roughly doubles the cost of production, while the returns are sometimes naught, making farming unsustainable. <img alt=\"The floods of 2019 destroyed sugarcane fields (left) and harvested tomatoes (right) in Khochi, a village adjacent to Bhendavade in Kolhapur district\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/04a-IMG_4651-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/04a-IMG_4651-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"The floods of 2019 destroyed sugarcane fields (left) and harvested tomatoes (right) in Khochi, a village adjacent to Bhendavade in Kolhapur district\"", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "83fde859-7ffc-4d74-8369-5ad9afbd821d": {"__data__": {"id_": "83fde859-7ffc-4d74-8369-5ad9afbd821d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, athletes get that sinking feeling", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "691e2bb2a2e23607726ddb12776718741b3d771d8ef27a1acdbf679955cd34ef"}, "3": {"node_id": "3fa8b2cc-cca7-4849-83d3-c24b0e9d16b1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "a1331f66ee880d1b681012447ab32a2a47662b472739f152fb76f5d36570ddd2"}}, "hash": "4540249fc7eb2bbf104bb4a56cf3e5674f767a7c88b6ce18d4f699e70459cdd5", "text": "class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/04b-IMG_0013-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/04b-IMG_0013-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:390px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain The floods of 2019 destroyed sugarcane fields (left) and harvested tomatoes (right) in Khochi, a village adjacent to Bhendavade in Kolhapur district The only way out is to borrow from private moneylenders at exorbitant interest rates, compounding the stress. \u201cAs the monthly repayment date approaches, you will see several people running to the hospital because of stress,\u201d Saniya adds. Mounting debt and the fear of another flood leave Saniya anxious most of the time. \u201cUsually, after any natural disaster, people are not able to put in the desired efforts to achieve their goals. It\u2019s not because they don't want to; they are unable to,\u201d says Kolhapur-based clinical psychologist Shalmali Ranmale Kakade. \u201cThis eventually leads to helplessness, frustration, and several sad emotions, which start affecting their mood and lead to anxiety.\u201d The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) has for the first time highlighted that climate change severely affects the mental health of people: \u201cMental health challenges, including anxiety and stress, are expected to increase under further global warming in all assessed regions, particularly for children, adolescents, elderly, and those with underlying health conditions.\u201d ***** Aishwarya Birajdar, 18, saw her dreams swept away by the floods of 2021. After the water receded, the sprinter and Taekwondo champion from Bhendavade spent over 100 hours across 15 days cleaning her house. \u201cThe stench just wouldn't go; the walls looked as if they could collapse anytime,\u201d she says. It took around 45 days for life to regain some sense of normalcy. \u201cIf you skip a day's training, you don't feel good,\u201d she explains. Making up for 45 days of lost training meant she had to work harder. \u201c[But] My stamina has fallen drastically because we are supposed to train double while eating half the food. This is unsustainable and causes a lot of tension,\u201d she says. <img alt=\"Sprinter and Taekwondo champion Aishwarya Birajdar (seated behind in the first photo) started experiencing heightened anxiety after the floods of 2021. She often skips her training sessions to help her family with chores on the farm and frequently makes do with one meal a day as the family struggles to make ends meet\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/05a-IMG_4700-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/05a-IMG_4700-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:400px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain <img alt=\"Sprinter and Taekwondo champion Aishwarya Birajdar (seated behind in the first photo) started experiencing heightened anxiety after the floods of 2021. She often skips her training sessions to help her family with chores on the farm and frequently makes do with one meal a day as the family struggles to make ends meet\" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/05b-IMG_4835-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_ge.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/05b-IMG_4835-SJ-In_Kolhapur_sportswomen_get_t.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:400px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sanket Jain Sprinter and Taekwondo champion Aishwarya Birajdar (seated behind in the first photo) started experiencing heightened anxiety after the floods of 2021.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3fa8b2cc-cca7-4849-83d3-c24b0e9d16b1": {"__data__": {"id_": "3fa8b2cc-cca7-4849-83d3-c24b0e9d16b1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "In Kolhapur, athletes get that sinking feeling", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "691e2bb2a2e23607726ddb12776718741b3d771d8ef27a1acdbf679955cd34ef"}, "2": {"node_id": "83fde859-7ffc-4d74-8369-5ad9afbd821d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-athletes-get-that-sinking-feeling/", "Author": "\n\n\n\n\nSanket Jain\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n", "Publisher": "People's Archive of Rural India", "Type": "Web"}, "hash": "4540249fc7eb2bbf104bb4a56cf3e5674f767a7c88b6ce18d4f699e70459cdd5"}}, "hash": "a1331f66ee880d1b681012447ab32a2a47662b472739f152fb76f5d36570ddd2", "text": "She often skips her training sessions to help her family with chores on the farm and frequently makes do with one meal a day as the family struggles to make ends meet After the flood water receded, Saniya\u2019s and Aishwarya\u2019s parents could not find any work for three months as the village struggled to get back on its feet. Javed, who also works as a mason to supplement his declining agricultural income, failed to get enough work with most of the construction in the area coming to a halt. As the fields remained inundated, Aishwarya\u2019s parents, who are tenant farmers and agricultural labourers, faced a similar experience. Given the loans to be repaid and the rising interest on them, the families had to resort to measures like eating less \u2013 Aishwarya and Saniya had to make do with just one meal a day for four months \u2013 and sometimes even skipping meals. The young sportswomen have lost count of the days they have had to sleep on empty stomach to help their parents make ends meet. All that deprivation has naturally affected their training and performance. \u201cMy body can no longer take rigorous workouts,\u201d says Saniya. When Saniya and Aishwarya first started to experience anxiety, they didn\u2019t take it too seriously \u2013 until they realised it was more prevalent among other athletes than they had imagined. \u201cAll our flood-affected athlete friends talk about the same [symptoms],\u201d says Aishwarya. \u201cThis has caused me so much stress that most of the time I feel I am depressed,\u201d adds Saniya. \u201cSince 2020 we\u2019ve observed that after the first rainfall, sometime in June, people start living in fear of floods,\u201d says Dr. Prasad Datar, taluka health officer of Hatkanangle. \u201cGiven that there is no solution to these floods, the fear keeps mounting, eventually leading to chronic illnesses and affecting people\u2019s mental health.\u201d Dr.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ede361a7-0ee6-4245-a9d1-f0b8f07e44ed": {"__data__": {"id_": "ede361a7-0ee6-4245-a9d1-f0b8f07e44ed", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://ruralindiaonline.org/en/articles/in-kolhapur-ath