rly evening hours. Besides, that extended heat is unrelenting. There was a time, some here recall, when an aandhi (sandstorm) whistled through villages almost every week and left behind a sheet of sand everywhere. Train tracks would get covered in sand, entire dunes would shift from place to place, a farmer sleeping in the courtyard would get covered too. \u201cThe westerly winds would bring the aandhi ,\u201d recalls retired schoolteacher Hardayalji. \u201cSand would fill even our sheets. Now that kind of a andhi does not rage here.\u201d <img alt=\"Left: The Chakravat drizzles have mostly disappeared, says Hardayalji Singh, retired teacher and landowner. Centre: Sushila Purohit, anganwadi worker in Sujangarh, says 'It is still hot in November. Right: Nirmal Prajapati, farm activist in Taranagar, says work hours have altered to adapt to the magnifying summer \" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/07a-IMG_0600-SJ.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/07a-IMG_0600-SJ.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:300px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sharmila Joshi <img alt=\"Left: The Chakravat drizzles have mostly disappeared, says Hardayalji Singh, retired teacher and landowner. Centre: Sushila Purohit, anganwadi worker in Sujangarh, says 'It is still hot in November. Right: Nirmal Prajapati, farm activist in Taranagar, says work hours have altered to adapt to the magnifying summer \" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/media/images/07b-IMG_0637-SJ--Blowing-hot-blowing-cold-.max-1400x1120.jpg\" src=\"/media/images/07b-IMG_0637-SJ--Blowing-hot-blowing-cold-in-.height-560.jpg\" style=\" height:300px;\"/> PHOTO \u2022 Sharmila Joshi <img alt=\"Left: The Chakravat drizzles have mostly disappeared, says Hardayalji Singh, retired teacher and landowner. Centre: Sushila Purohit, anganwadi worker in Sujangarh, says 'It is still hot in November. Right: Nirmal Prajapati, farm activist in Taranagar, says work hours have altered to adapt to the magnifying summer \" class=\"lazyload\" data-src=\"/med